While researching cybercrime in the Indian context, I was most surprised by the sheer psychological precision of "Social Engineering." I previously assumed that digital theft required complex coding or server hacking; however, I realized that most victims are compromised through simple manipulation of trust and urgency. The fact that scammers successfully exploit the "Golden Hour"—the narrow window before a victim realizes their mistake—to move funds through a chain of mule accounts is both fascinating and alarming.

As a direct result of this project, I am changing my habit of "convenience-based clicking." I used to reflexively click links in SMS or WhatsApp messages for tracking deliveries or "verifying" accounts. Moving forward, I will adopt a "Zero Trust" policy: I will manually navigate to the official app or website for any notification I receive. This small shift in digital hygiene significantly reduces my vulnerability to phishing and UPI-based deception.
